{{afc comment|1=redirect [[Shizuri]] to this article in the future[[User:Immanuelle|'''Immanuel'''le]] ❤️💚💙 [[User_talk:Immanuelle|(talk to the cutest Wikipedian)]] 05:47, 3 December 2023 (UTC)}}
{{ill|Takehazuchi|ja|天羽槌雄神}} (天羽槌雄神) is the Japanese god of weaving<ref name="Nihongi6970">{{cite wikisource|author=Aston|date=1896|Nihongi: Chronicles of Japan from the Earliest Times to A.D. 697|chapter=Book II|pages=69–70}}</ref> Also known as Shizuri.<ref name="mizue-2">{{Cite web |last=Mizue |first=Mori |title=Shizuri |url=https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/id=9154 |website=[[Kokugakuin University]] Encyclopedia of Shinto}}</ref>
Appended to the two passages is the mention of a star deity named [[Amatsu-Mikaboshi]] who resisted till the end, and whom Takemikazuchi and Futsunushi were particularly eager to vanquish. The latter passage states that the being who subdued the star god, referred to as {{Nihongo|''Iwai no nushi''|斎の大人}} is enshrined at Katori, hinting that it might be [[Futsunushi]].<ref>{{cite book |author=寺島良安 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h98EAAAAMAAJ |title=和漢三才図会 |author2=島田勇雄, 樋口元巳 |publisher=平凡社 |year=1985 |isbn=9784582804478 |volume=10 |page=71}} subscribes to this view</ref><ref name="Nihongi6970" /> However, the earlier passage says a god named {{Interlanguage link multi|Takehazuchi|ja|建葉槌命|vertical-align=sup}} was the vanquisher of the star god.<ref>{{Harvnb|宇治谷|1988}} 『日本書紀』上 p.64, 58</ref> 
[[ja:天羽槌雄神]]
[[File:Bentenjima on Inasa Beach.jpg|right|thumb|250x250px|Inasa Beach ([[:ja:稲佐の浜|稲佐の浜]] ''Inasa-no-hama'') in [[Izumo, Shimane|Izumo]], [[Shimane Prefecture]], where the myth places Ōkuninushi's meeting with the messengers of heaven and his surrender to them.]]


After Ōkuninushi's assent and withdrawal, the two messengers proceeded to destroy everyone and everything who refused to submit to their authority. They then send the god of weaving, Takehazuchi (建葉槌), to subdue the star god [[Amatsu-Mikaboshi|Kagaseo]] (香香背男), the last remaining rebel against Takamagahara (''Nihon Shoki'').<ref name="Nihongi6970" /> After the resistance was gone the [[Tenson kōrin]] could begin.<ref name="mizue-2" />

The [[Kogo Shūi]] identifies him with Amenohatsuchio the ancestorr of the Shizuri clan who did weaving.<ref name="mizue-2" />

At [[Shitori Shrine (Tottori)|Shitori Shrine]] {{ill|Takehazuchi|ja|天羽槌雄神}} and {{ill|Shitateruhime|lt=Shitateruhime-no-Mikoto|ja|下照比売}} are worshipped as weaving gods<ref name="mizue-2" />.

== Content frrom [[Shitori Shrine (Tottori)]] ==
The origins of [[Shitori Shrine (Tottori)|Shitori Shrine]] are unknown. Although there is no documentary evidence, it is believed that it began as the family shrine for the {{Nihongo|Shitori clan|倭文氏}} of [[Kofun period]] craftsmen who weavers, who regarded {{ill|Takehazuchi|lt=Takehazuchi-no-Mikoto|ja|天羽槌雄神}} as their ancestor. However, the shrine's legends are all centered around {{ill|Shitateruhime|lt=Shitateruhime-no-Mikoto|ja|下照比売}}, whom the shrine legend claims arrived in this location from [[Izumo Taisha|Izumo]] by boat. She established her residence on the mountain behind this shrine, and after her death, she was buried in a ''[[kofun]]'' constructed in the shrine's precincts.<ref name="Yoshiki">{{cite book |last1=Yoshiki |first1=Emi |title=Zenkoku 'Ichinomiya' tettei gaido |date=2007 |publisher=PHP Institute |isbn=978-4569669304 |language=Japanese}}</ref>

==See Also==

* {{ill|Shitateruhime|lt=Shitateruhime-no-Mikoto|ja|下照比売|draft}}

