{{ill|Katsuragi Shitori niimasu Amenohaikazuchi no Mikoto Shrine|ja|葛木倭文座天羽雷命神社|12=draft}}|type=Shinto|name=Takehazuchi|script_name=天羽槌雄神|other_names=Ama no Hazuchi|father={{ill|Amanohiwashi no Mikoto|ja|天日鷲神|simple|user:immanuelle/Amanohiwashi no Mikoto|12=draft}}}}
{{ill|Takehazuchi|ja|天羽槌雄神|simple|User:Immanuelle/Takehazuchi|en:draft|8=fr|12=draft}} (天羽槌雄神){{efn|also read as Amenohazuchi}} is the Japanese goddess of weaving<ref name="Nihongi6970">{{cite wikisource|author=Aston|date=1896|Nihongi: Chronicles of Japan from the Earliest Times to A.D. 697|chapter=Book II|pages=69–70}}</ref> Also known as Shizuri.<ref name="mizue-2">{{Cite web |last=Mizue |first=Mori |title=Shizuri |url=https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/id=9154 |website={{ill|Kokugakuin University|en}} Encyclopedia of Shinto}}</ref>

She is believed to be a fifth generation descendant of {{ill|Takamimusubi|en|12=draft}} most likely through [[Sukunabikona]] due to the other associations of him.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|title=天羽槌雄神（あめのはづちのおのかみ）　・建葉槌命（たけはづちのみこと）／日本の神々の話　 : 四季歩のつれづれ|url=http://tamtom.blog44.fc2.com/blog-entry-2646.html|access-date=2024-05-23|website=tamtom.blog44.fc2.com}}</ref>

She decorated the streamers on the [[Masakaki]] tree used to lure out [[Amaterasu]] from the cave.<ref>{{Cite web|title=神々の庭：天羽槌雄神 (あめのはずちおのかみ)|url=http://shinto.fugarden.com/gosaishin_amenohazutio.html|access-date=2024-05-23|website=shinto.fugarden.com}}</ref> 

She is a warrior who vanquished the rebellious star god {{ill|Amatsu-Mikaboshi|en}} during the {{ill|Tenson kōrin|en|12=draft}}.<ref name="宇治谷 1988">{{Harvnb|宇治谷|1988}} 『日本書紀』上 p.64, 58</ref><ref name="Nihongi6970" /><ref name="mizue-2" />


Appended to the two passages of the subjugation of the earth in the [[Nihon Shoki|Nihon Shoki]] and the [[Kojiki|Kojiki]] is the mention of a star deity named {{ill|Amatsu-Mikaboshi|en}} who resisted till the end, and whom {{ill|Takemikazuchi|en|4=fr|12=draft}} and {{ill|Futsunushi|en|4=fr|12=draft}} were particularly eager to vanquish. The latter passage states that the being who subdued the star god, referred to as {{Nihongo|''Iwai no nushi''|斎の大人}} is enshrined at Katori, hinting that it might be {{ill|Futsunushi|en|4=fr|12=draft}}.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h98EAAAAMAAJ|title=和漢三才図会|author=寺島良安|author2=島田勇雄, 樋口元巳|publisher=平凡社|year=1985|isbn=9784582804478|volume=10|page=71}} subscribes to this view</ref><ref name="Nihongi6970" /> However, the earlier passage says a god named {{ill|Takehazuchi|ja|天羽槌雄神|simple|User:Immanuelle/Takehazuchi|en:draft||fr|12=draft}} was the vanquisher of the star god.<ref name="宇治谷 1988" /><ref>{{Cite web|date=2024-03-20|title=Hoshinokamikakaseo {{!}} 國學院大學デジタルミュージアム|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240320033035/https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/id=9400|access-date=2024-03-20|website=web.archive.org}}</ref>

After Ōkuninushi's assent and withdrawal, the two messengers proceeded to destroy everyone and everything who refused to submit to their authority. They then send the god of weaving, Takehazuchi (建葉槌), to subdue the star god {{ill|Amatsu-Mikaboshi|lt=Kagaseo|en|12=draft}} (香香背男), the last remaining rebel against Takamagahara (''Nihon Shoki'').<ref name="Nihongi6970" /> After the resistance was gone the {{ill|Tenson kōrin|en}} could begin.<ref name="mizue-2" />

It is believed it She may either have also been a war goddess based on the "take" in her name analogous to {{ill|Takemikazuchi|en|4=fr|12=draft}} or that She wove the stars into fabric, taming them.<ref name=":0" />

The {{ill|Kogo Shūi|en}} identifies him with Amenohatsuchio the ancestor of the Shizuri clan who did weaving.<ref name="mizue-2" />

At {{ill|Shitori Shrine (Tottori)|lt=Shitori Shrine|en|4=fr|5=Shitori-jinja|12=draft}} {{ill|Takehazuchi|ja|天羽槌雄神|simple|User:Immanuelle/Takehazuchi|en:draft|8=fr|12=draft}} and {{ill|Shitateruhime|lt=Shitateruhime-no-Mikoto|ja|シタテルヒメ|simple|User:Immanuelle/Shitateruhime|en:draft|8=fr|12=draft}} are worshipped as weaving gods<ref name="mizue-2" />. 

