She is believed to be a fifth generation descendant of {{ill|Takamimusubi|en|12=draft}} most likely through [[Sukunabikona]] due to the other associations of him.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|title=天羽槌雄神（あめのはづちのおのかみ）　・建葉槌命（たけはづちのみこと）／日本の神々の話　 : 四季歩のつれづれ|url=http://tamtom.blog44.fc2.com/blog-entry-2646.html|access-date=2024-05-23|website=tamtom.blog44.fc2.com}}</ref>

She decorated the streamers on the [[Masakaki]] tree used to lure out [[Amaterasu]] from the cave.<ref>{{Cite web|title=神々の庭：天羽槌雄神 (あめのはずちおのかみ)|url=http://shinto.fugarden.com/gosaishin_amenohazutio.html|access-date=2024-05-23|website=shinto.fugarden.com}}</ref> 

She is a warrior who vanquished the rebellious star god {{ill|Amatsu-Mikaboshi|en}} during the {{ill|Tenson kōrin|en|12=draft}}.<ref name="宇治谷 1988">{{Harvnb|宇治谷|1988}} 『日本書紀』上 p.64, 58</ref><ref name="Nihongi6970" /><ref name="mizue-2" />


Appended to the two passages of the subjugation of the earth in the [[Nihon Shoki|Nihon Shoki]] and the [[Kojiki|Kojiki]] is the mention of a star deity named {{ill|Amatsu-Mikaboshi|en}} who resisted till the end, and whom {{ill|Takemikazuchi|en|4=fr|12=draft}} and {{ill|Futsunushi|en|4=fr|12=draft}} were particularly eager to vanquish. The latter passage states that the being who subdued the star god, referred to as {{Nihongo|''Iwai no nushi''|斎の大人}} is enshrined at Katori, hinting that it might be {{ill|Futsunushi|en|4=fr|12=draft}}.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h98EAAAAMAAJ|title=和漢三才図会|author=寺島良安|author2=島田勇雄, 樋口元巳|publisher=平凡社|year=1985|isbn=9784582804478|volume=10|page=71}} subscribes to this view</ref><ref name="Nihongi6970" /> However, the earlier passage says a god named {{ill|Takehazuchi|ja|天羽槌雄神|1=Takehazuchi|2=ja|3=天羽槌雄神|4=zh|5=天羽槌雄神|6=fr|7=Takehazuchi|lt=Takehazuchi|simple|User:Immanuelle/Takehazuchi|en:draft||fr|12=draft}} was the vanquisher of the star god.<ref name="宇治谷 1988" /><ref>{{Cite web|date=2024-03-20|title=Hoshinokamikakaseo {{!}} 國學院大學デジタルミュージアム|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240320033035/https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/id=9400|access-date=2024-03-20|website=web.archive.org}}</ref>

After Ōkuninushi's assent and withdrawal, the two messengers proceeded to destroy everyone and everything who refused to submit to their authority. They then send the god of weaving, Takehazuchi (建葉槌), to subdue the star god {{ill|Amatsu-Mikaboshi|lt=Kagaseo|en|12=draft}} (香香背男), the last remaining rebel against Takamagahara (''Nihon Shoki'').<ref name="Nihongi6970" /> After the resistance was gone the {{ill|Tenson kōrin|en}} could begin.<ref name="mizue-2" />

It is believed it She may either have also been a war goddess based on the "take" in her name analogous to {{ill|Takemikazuchi|en|4=fr|12=draft}} or that She wove the stars into fabric, taming them.<ref name=":0" />

The {{ill|Kogo Shūi|en}} identifies him with Amenohatsuchio the ancestor of the Shizuri clan who did weaving.<ref name="mizue-2" />

At {{ill|Shitori Shrine (Tottori)|lt=Shitori Shrine|en|4=fr|5=Shitori-jinja|12=draft}} {{ill|Takehazuchi|ja|天羽槌雄神|1=Takehazuchi|2=ja|3=天羽槌雄神|4=zh|5=天羽槌雄神|6=fr|7=Takehazuchi|lt=Takehazuchi|simple|User:Immanuelle/Takehazuchi|en:draft|8=fr|12=draft}} and {{ill|Shitateruhime|lt=Shitateruhime-no-Mikoto|ja|シタテルヒメ|simple|User:Immanuelle/Shitateruhime|en:draft|8=fr|12=draft}} are worshipped as weaving gods<ref name="mizue-2" />. 

== Overview ==

Takehazuchi no Kami is mentioned in the ''{{ill|Kogo Shūi|ja|古語拾遺|12=draft}}'' as ''Takehazuchi no Kami''. In the ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft}}'', she is referred to as {{ill|Takehatsuchi-no-Mikoto|ja|建葉槌命|12=draft}} and {{ill|Shidori deity|ja|倭文神|12=draft}}. In the ''{{ill|Shinsen Shōjiroku|ja|新撰姓氏録|1=Shinsen Shōjiroku|12=draft}}'', she is called {{ill|Toyohachi-no-Mikoto|ja|止与波知命|12=draft}} in the Yamashiro Province section and {{ill|Amenoha-no-Mikoto|ja|天破命|12=draft}} in another entry. The ''Anwa Province Imbe Family Genealogy'' (安房国忌部家系), which includes the "Ibe no Sukune Honkeicho" (齋部宿祢本系帳), records her name as {{ill|Ameno Haikazuchi-no-Mikoto|ja|天羽雷雄命|12=draft}} and also lists {{ill|Takehazuchi-no-Mikoto|ja|武羽槌命|12=draft}} and {{ill|Toyohazuji-no-Mikoto|ja|止与波豆知命|12=draft}} as alternative names.<ref>{{cite book|和書 |title=安房国忌部家系|chapter=齋部宿祢本系帳|section=天羽雷雄命|doi=10.11501/2538213|url={{NDLDC|2538213/55}} }} ({{ill|National Diet Library Digital Collections|ja|国立国会図書館デジタルコレクション|12=draft}})</ref>

She is said to have woven sacred cloth (''aya'') to lure {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照大神|1=Amaterasu|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|12=draft}} out of the {{ill|Ama-no-Iwato|ja|天の岩戸|12=draft}}. The cloth she wove is called {{ill|Shidori cloth|ja|倭文布|12=draft}} or simply ''Shidori'' (倭文), a term referring to a type of woven fabric. Other weaving deities include {{ill|Takuhatachichihime-no-Mikoto|ja|栲幡千々姫命|12=draft}} and {{ill|Amanotatakahime-no-Mikoto|ja|天棚機姫神|lt=Ame-no-Tanabatahime|1=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|2=ja|3=天棚機姫神|lt=Ame-no-Tanabatahime|1=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|2=ja|3=天棚機姫神|4=de|5=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|6=fr|7=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|8=zh|9=天棚機姫神|10=nl|11=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|4=de|5=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|6=fr|7=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|8=zh|9=天棚機姫神|10=nl|11=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|lt=Ame-no-Tanabatahime|1=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|2=ja|3=天棚機姫神|lt=Ame-no-Tanabatahime|1=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|2=ja|3=天棚機姫神|4=de|5=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|6=fr|7=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|8=zh|9=天棚機姫神|10=nl|11=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|4=de|5=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|6=fr|7=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|8=zh|9=天棚機姫神|10=nl|11=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|12=draft}}, but Takehazuchi no Kami is revered as the '''supreme ancestor of weaving'''. She is also the '''ancestor of the {{ill|Shidori clan|ja|倭文氏|12=draft}}'''.

She is worshipped as the '''goddess of weaving''' in '''{{ill|Shidori Shrines|ja|倭文神社|12=draft}}''', '''{{ill|Shizu Shrine|ja|静神社|12=draft}}''', '''Hattori Shrines''', and others throughout Japan.

== Genealogy ==

In ''{{ill|Kogo Shūi|ja|古語拾遺|12=draft}}'', she is called the '''far ancestor of the {{ill|Shidori clan|ja|倭文氏|12=draft}}'''. In ''{{ill|Sendai Kujihongi|ja|先代旧事本紀|12=draft}}'', she is described as the '''distant ancestor of the {{ill|Shidori-no-Mikoto|ja|倭文造|12=draft}}'''.

== Legends and Deeds ==

Takehazuchi no Kami appears in the ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft}}'' under the name {{ill|Takehatsuchi-no-Mikoto|ja|建葉槌命|12=draft}}. She is said to have '''subjugated the star deity''' '''{{ill|Amanomikaboshi|ja|天津甕星|12=draft}} (also known as Kagaseo no Kami)''', whom '''{{ill|Takemikazuchi-no-Kami|ja|武甕槌命|12=draft}}''' and '''{{ill|Futsunushi-no-Kami|ja|経津主神|12=draft}}''' were unable to pacify.<ref>{{Cite book|和書|author=植松安|date=1920-06|title=仮名日本書紀|volume=上巻|pages=87–88|publisher=大同館書店|url={{NDLDC|961006/117}} |doi=10.11501/961006 }} ({{ill|National Diet Library Digital Collections|ja|国立国会図書館デジタルコレクション|12=draft}})</ref>

==Descendant clans==

{{ill|Nagahata clan|ja|長幡部連|12=draft}}, {{ill|Shidori clan|ja|倭文氏|12=draft}}, {{ill|Tanabe clan|ja|田辺宿禰|12=draft}}, {{ill|Takehara clan|ja|竹原氏|12=draft}}, {{ill|Okura clan|ja|巨椋連|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ōkura Okihajime clan|ja|大椋置始連|12=draft}}, {{ill|Imaki clan|ja|今木連|12=draft}}, {{ill|Yuge clan|ja|弓削氏|12=draft}}, {{ill|Tame clan|ja|多米連|12=draft}}, {{ill|Minu clan|ja|美努連|12=draft}} ({{ill|Minokuni Rulers|ja|三野県主|12=draft}}), {{ill|Tottoribe clan|ja|鳥取部連|12=draft}}, {{ill|Jingu clan|ja|神宮部造|12=draft}}, {{ill|Agatanoinukai clan|ja|県犬養氏|1=Agata no Inukai clan|12=draft}}

== Shrines ==<!--== Content from [[Shitori Shrine (Tottori)]] == -->
{{ill|Takehazuchi|ja|天羽槌雄神|1=Takehazuchi|2=ja|3=天羽槌雄神|4=zh|5=天羽槌雄神|6=fr|7=Takehazuchi|lt=Takehazuchi|simple|User:Immanuelle/Takehazuchi|en:draft|8=fr|12=draft}} is believed to be the ancestor of the {{Nihongo|Shitori clan|倭文氏}} of {{ill|Shitori Shrine (Tottori)|lt=Shitori Shrine|en|12=draft}}<ref name="Yoshiki" />.<ref name="mizue-2" /> 

However, the legends of {{ill|Shitori Shrine (Tottori)|lt=Shitori Shrine|en|12=draft}} are all centered around {{ill|Shitateruhime|lt=Shitateruhime-no-Mikoto|ja|シタテルヒメ|simple|User:Immanuelle/Shitateruhime|en:draft|8=fr|12=draft}}, whom the shrine legend claims arrived in this location from {{ill|Izumo-taisha|lt=Izumo|en|12=draft}} by boat. She established her residence on the mountain behind this shrine, and after her death, she was buried in a ''{{ill|kofun|en}}'' constructed in the shrine's precincts.<ref name="Yoshiki">{{cite book|last1=Yoshiki |first1=Emi |title=Zenkoku 'Ichinomiya' tettei gaido |date=2007 |publisher=PHP Institute |isbn=978-4569669304 |language=Japanese|12=draft}}</ref>
