At {{ill|Shitori Shrine (Tottori)|lt=Shitori Shrine|en|4=fr|5=Shitori-jinja|12=draft|12=draft}} {{ill|Takehazuchi|ja|天羽槌雄神|1=Takehazuchi|2=ja|3=天羽槌雄神|4=zh|5=天羽槌雄神|6=fr|7=Takehazuchi|lt=Takehazuchi|simple|User:Immanuelle/Takehazuchi|en:draft|8=fr|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Shitateruhime|lt=Shitateruhime-no-Mikoto|ja|シタテルヒメ|simple|User:Immanuelle/Shitateruhime|en:draft|8=fr|12=draft|12=draft}} are worshipped as weaving gods<ref name="mizue-2" />. 

== Overview ==

Takehazuchi no Kami is mentioned in the ''{{ill|Kogo Shūi|ja|古語拾遺|12=draft|12=draft}}'' as ''Takehazuchi no Kami''. In the ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft|12=draft}}'', she is referred to as {{ill|Takehatsuchi-no-Mikoto|ja|建葉槌命|1=Takehazuchi|2=ja|3=天羽槌雄神|4=zh|5=天羽槌雄神|6=fr|7=Takehazuchi|lt=Takehazuchi|lt=Takehazuchi-no-Mikoto|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Shidori deity|ja|倭文神|1=Takehazuchi|2=ja|3=天羽槌雄神|4=zh|5=天羽槌雄神|6=fr|7=Takehazuchi|lt=Takehazuchi|lt=Takehazuchi-no-Mikoto|simple|Takehazuchi|fr|Takehazuchi|lt=Takehazuchi|lt=Shizuri-no-Kami|12=draft|12=draft}}. In the ''{{ill|Shinsen Shōjiroku|ja|新撰姓氏録|1=Shinsen Shōjiroku|12=draft|12=draft}}'', she is called {{ill|Toyohachi-no-Mikoto|ja|止与波知命|12=draft|12=draft}} in the Yamashiro Province section and {{ill|Amenoha-no-Mikoto|ja|天破命|12=draft|12=draft}} in another entry. The ''Anwa Province Imbe Family Genealogy'' (安房国忌部家系), which includes the "Ibe no Sukune Honkeicho" (齋部宿祢本系帳), records her name as {{ill|Ameno Haikazuchi-no-Mikoto|ja|天羽雷雄命|12=draft|12=draft}} and also lists {{ill|Takehazuchi-no-Mikoto|ja|武羽槌命|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Toyohazuji-no-Mikoto|ja|止与波豆知命|12=draft|12=draft}} as alternative names.<ref>{{cite book|和書 |title=安房国忌部家系|chapter=齋部宿祢本系帳|section=天羽雷雄命|doi=10.11501/2538213|url={{NDLDC|2538213/55}} }} ({{ill|National Diet Library Digital Collections|ja|国立国会図書館デジタルコレクション|12=draft|12=draft}})</ref>

She is said to have woven sacred cloth (''aya'') to lure {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照大神|1=Amaterasu|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|12=draft|12=draft}} out of the {{ill|Ama-no-Iwato|ja|天の岩戸|12=draft|12=draft}}. The cloth she wove is called {{ill|Shidori cloth|ja|倭文布|12=draft|12=draft}} or simply ''Shidori'' (倭文), a term referring to a type of woven fabric. Other weaving deities include {{ill|Takuhatachichihime-no-Mikoto|ja|栲幡千々姫命|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Amanotatakahime-no-Mikoto|ja|天棚機姫神|lt=Ame-no-Tanabatahime|1=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|2=ja|3=天棚機姫神|lt=Ame-no-Tanabatahime|1=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|2=ja|3=天棚機姫神|4=de|5=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|6=fr|7=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|8=zh|9=天棚機姫神|10=nl|11=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|4=de|5=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|6=fr|7=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|8=zh|9=天棚機姫神|10=nl|11=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|lt=Ame-no-Tanabatahime|1=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|2=ja|3=天棚機姫神|lt=Ame-no-Tanabatahime|1=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|2=ja|3=天棚機姫神|4=de|5=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|6=fr|7=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|8=zh|9=天棚機姫神|10=nl|11=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|4=de|5=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|6=fr|7=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|8=zh|9=天棚機姫神|10=nl|11=Tanabatabime-no-Mikoto|12=draft|12=draft}}, but Takehazuchi no Kami is revered as the '''supreme ancestor of weaving'''. She is also the '''ancestor of the {{ill|Shizuri clan|ja|倭文部|1=Shizuri clan|2=ja|3=倭文氏|4=zh|5=倭文氏|6=de|7=Shizuri Clan|8=fr|9=Clan Shizuri|lt=Shizuri Bemin (vassals of the Shizuri clan)|lt=Shizuri clan|12=draft|12=draft}}'''.

She is worshipped as the '''goddess of weaving''' in '''{{ill|Shidori Shrines|ja|倭文神社|12=draft|12=draft}}''', '''{{ill|Shizu Shrine|ja|静神社|12=draft|12=draft}}''', '''Hattori Shrines''', and others throughout Japan.

== Genealogy ==

In ''{{ill|Kogo Shūi|ja|古語拾遺|12=draft|12=draft}}'', she is called the '''far ancestor of the {{ill|Shizuri clan|ja|倭文部|1=Shizuri clan|2=ja|3=倭文氏|4=zh|5=倭文氏|6=de|7=Shizuri Clan|8=fr|9=Clan Shizuri|lt=Shizuri Bemin (vassals of the Shizuri clan)|lt=Shizuri clan|12=draft|12=draft}}'''. In ''{{ill|Sendai Kujihongi|ja|先代旧事本紀|12=draft|12=draft}}'', she is described as the '''distant ancestor of the {{ill|Shidori-no-Mikoto|ja|倭文造|12=draft|12=draft}}'''.

== Legends and Deeds ==

Takehazuchi no Kami appears in the ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft|12=draft}}'' under the name {{ill|Takehatsuchi-no-Mikoto|ja|建葉槌命|1=Takehazuchi|2=ja|3=天羽槌雄神|4=zh|5=天羽槌雄神|6=fr|7=Takehazuchi|lt=Takehazuchi|lt=Takehazuchi-no-Mikoto|12=draft|12=draft}}. She is said to have '''subjugated the star deity''' '''{{ill|Amanomikaboshi|ja|天津甕星|1=Amatsu-Mikaboshi|2=zh|3=天津甕星|4=ja|5=天津甕星|6=ru|7=Амацумикабоси|8=tr|9=Amatsu Mikaboşi|10=mni|11=ꯑꯃꯠꯁꯨ-ꯃꯤꯀꯕꯣꯁꯤ|12=th|13=อามัตสึมิกาโบชิ|15=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} (also known as Kagaseo no Kami)''', whom '''{{ill|Takemikazuchi-no-Kami|ja|武甕槌命|12=draft|12=draft}}''' and '''{{ill|Futsunushi-no-Kami|ja|経津主神|12=draft|12=draft}}''' were unable to pacify.<ref>{{Cite book|和書|author=植松安|date=1920-06|title=仮名日本書紀|volume=上巻|pages=87–88|publisher=大同館書店|url={{NDLDC|961006/117}} |doi=10.11501/961006 }} ({{ill|National Diet Library Digital Collections|ja|国立国会図書館デジタルコレクション|12=draft|12=draft}})</ref>

==Descendant clans==

{{ill|Nagahata clan|ja|長幡部連|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Shizuri clan|ja|倭文部|1=Shizuri clan|2=ja|3=倭文氏|4=zh|5=倭文氏|6=de|7=Shizuri Clan|8=fr|9=Clan Shizuri|lt=Shizuri Bemin (vassals of the Shizuri clan)|lt=Shizuri clan|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Tanabe clan|ja|田辺宿禰|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Takehara clan|ja|竹原氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Okura clan|ja|巨椋連|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ōkura Okihajime clan|ja|大椋置始連|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Imaki clan|ja|今木連|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Yuge clan|ja|弓削氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Tame clan|ja|多米連|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Minu clan|ja|美努連|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Minokuni Rulers|ja|三野県主|12=draft|12=draft}}), {{ill|Tottoribe clan|ja|鳥取部連|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Jingu clan|ja|神宮部造|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Agatanoinukai clan|ja|県犬養氏|1=Agata no Inukai clan|12=draft|12=draft}}

== Shrines ==
{{ill|Takehazuchi|ja|天羽槌雄神|1=Takehazuchi|2=ja|3=天羽槌雄神|4=zh|5=天羽槌雄神|6=fr|7=Takehazuchi|lt=Takehazuchi|simple|User:Immanuelle/Takehazuchi|en:draft|8=fr|12=draft|12=draft}} is believed to be the ancestor of the {{Nihongo|Shitori clan|倭文氏}} of {{ill|Shitori Shrine (Tottori)|lt=Shitori Shrine|en|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref name="Yoshiki" />.<ref name="mizue-2" /> 

However, the legends of {{ill|Shitori Shrine (Tottori)|lt=Shitori Shrine|en|12=draft|12=draft}} are all centered around {{ill|Shitateruhime|lt=Shitateruhime-no-Mikoto|ja|シタテルヒメ|simple|User:Immanuelle/Shitateruhime|en:draft|8=fr|12=draft|12=draft}}, whom the shrine legend claims arrived in this location from {{ill|Izumo-taisha|lt=Izumo|en|12=draft|12=draft}} by boat. She established her residence on the mountain behind this shrine, and after her death, she was buried in a ''{{ill|kofun|en}}'' constructed in the shrine's precincts.<ref name="Yoshiki">{{cite book|last1=Yoshiki |first1=Emi |title=Zenkoku 'Ichinomiya' tettei gaido |date=2007 |publisher=PHP Institute |isbn=978-4569669304 |language=Japanese|12=draft|12=draft}}</ref>
